Based on the provided context, Chandrayaan-1 is the first instrumented Indian mission to the Moon and the first ISRO venture to leave Earth's gravity. It is a lunar exploration mission aimed at high-resolution remote sensing of the lunar surface in visible, near infrared (NIR), low energy X-ray, and high-energy X-ray regions. The mission includes eleven state-of-the-art instruments for preparing a three-dimensional atlas of both the near and far sides of the Moon, conducting chemical and mineralogical mapping of the entire lunar surface, and exploring the Moon from close quarters as it descends, till impact.

Chandrayaan-1 is also an example of international collaboration towards exploring the Moon, with six scientific payloads from NASA, ESA, and Bulgaria onboard. The mission will provide a comprehensive understanding of the Moon's surface and subsurface, enabling research in basic science and engineering in India.

